500|$|Following the report's publication, the {{administration}} of US President Franklin D. Roosevelt turned to the newly created <b>War</b> <b>Refugee</b> Board (WRB) established {{as a result of}} activism by the [...] "Bergson Group" [...] led by Hillel Kook [...] and later by Treasury Secretary Henry Morgenthau, Jr and team in search of a solution to the humanitarian crisis in Hungary. In spring 1944, President Roosevelt dispatched US Treasury Department official Iver C. Olsen to Stockholm {{as a representative of the}} WRB. Olsen was tasked specifically by the President with finding a way to aid the Hungarian Jews. This, however, was not the sole reason for Olsen being posted to Sweden. In addition to his duties with the WRB, Olsen was also secretly functioning as the chief of currency operations for the Stockholm branch of the Office of Strategic Services (OSS), the United States' wartime espionage service.|$|E
